                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 10044/145.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Ambassador <persName type="from">Leishman</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Pera</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1909-04-19">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 19, 1909</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Mr. Leishman says that while the situation at Adana is calmer, similar trouble is
                    extending to the neighboring districts; that about 20,000 troops of the Third
                    Army Corps, which is supporting the constitution, are within 20 miles of
                    Constantinople and more arriving hourly. Mr. Leishman adds that the mutinous
                    troops of the capital and reactionary instigators of the recent revolt fear the
                    consequences of their action and are greatly alarmed.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
